{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524547"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:05:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:05:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14007"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14007"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.11,0.02,0.2,0.62]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6656"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59387"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6656"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14007"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44793"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1598"},{"type":"tags","id":"8103"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13667"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59387"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-day history of feeling generally unwell with malaise, anorexia, and low-grade fever. He reports feeling very tired and unable to work. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications, though he has been using over-the-counter diclofenac for his symptoms. He drinks two glasses of wine daily and has a 20 pack-year smoking history. He has not travelled recently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears fatigued. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 128/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. On general inspection, the following appearance is noted on his back (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the changes on his back?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Drug allergy","Lyme disease","Hives","Granuloma annulare","Cupping"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows multiple circular, well-demarcated areas of ecchymosis arranged in a symmetrical pattern on the patient\u0027s back. \u003Cstrong\u003ECupping\u003C/strong\u003E therapy, a traditional medicine practice where glass cups create suction on the skin, produces these characteristic circular bruises. While the patient was initially reluctant to disclose this information, he had undergone cupping therapy several days earlier, likely seeking relief from his non-specific symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug allergy\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a maculopapular or urticarial rash that is more diffuse and irregular in pattern. While the patient has been taking diclofenac, the perfectly circular, bruise-like lesions are not consistent with a drug reaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELyme disease\u003C/strong\u003E classically presents with erythema migrans, a bull\u0027s-eye rash that typically appears at the site of a tick bite. The rash is usually single, expanding, and has central clearing. Multiple symmetrical circular lesions would be highly unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHives\u003C/strong\u003E (urticaria) are raised, erythematous, and pruritic wheals that are typically pale in the centre with surrounding erythema. They are transient, usually lasting less than 24 hours in one location, and do not cause bruising.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranuloma annulare\u003C/strong\u003E presents as firm, flesh-coloured to erythematous annular plaques, often on the dorsal surfaces of extremities. The lesions are not bruise-like and develop gradually rather than appearing suddenly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECupping is increasingly popular in Western countries as a form of complementary medicine. The circular marks are caused by capillary rupture from the negative pressure created by the cups. While usually harmless, healthcare providers should be able to recognise these marks to avoid unnecessary investigations or misdiagnosis as physical abuse.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cupping therapy produces characteristic circular ecchymoses that can be mistaken for signs of physical abuse or other skin conditions.","A thorough social history including complementary medicine use is important when evaluating unusual skin findings.","Non-specific symptoms like malaise and fever may prompt patients to seek alternative therapies."],"references":["Choi TY, And L, Ku B, et al.  Evidence Map of Cupping Therapy J. Clin. Med. 2021, 10, 1750. https://doi.org/10.3390/jcm10081750"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44793"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14007"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20919"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20919"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/CKnA6IDTZmmbpAWFYtjQZnVtl7Fco5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/CKnA6IDTZmmbpAWFYtjQZnVtl7Fco5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44793"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-07T14:36:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11